&gt;&gt; Okay. Our photographer
is right there waiting

00:24:45.290 --> 00:24:52.150
for a great picture and then
I'm going to get out of it.

00:24:52.150 --> 00:24:53.450
Okay. Now of you three.

00:24:53.450 --> 00:24:54.750
&gt;&gt; Oh.

00:24:54.750 --> 00:24:56.050
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:24:56.050 --> 00:24:57.350
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:24:57.350 --> 00:25:01.380
&gt;&gt; Nice. Okay, Shawn do
you need any other shots?

00:25:01.380 --> 00:25:02.680
You're good.

00:25:02.680 --> 00:25:03.980
All right.

00:25:03.980 --> 00:25:06.330
Excellent, now Jacqueline
and Dr. Hayden are going

00:25:06.330 --> 00:25:09.180
to have a little conversation
and about ten minutes

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:11.490
into the conversation,
Jacqueline's going to come

00:25:11.490 --> 00:25:15.440
up here and make some remarks,
especially for all of us,

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:18.360
and then we'll open
it up for questions

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:20.880
from the audience
starting with our students

00:25:20.880 --> 00:25:22.380
from Brooklyn Middle School.

00:25:22.380 --> 00:25:24.680
Thanks.

00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:28.660
&gt;&gt; Well, this is just
an honor for all of us

00:25:28.660 --> 00:25:30.570
and a special pleasure?

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:31.870
&gt;&gt; Yay [laughter]

00:25:31.870 --> 00:25:36.180
&gt;&gt; Special, special,
pleasure yes, my copy.

00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:41.210
Yes, my copy [laughter]
just saying,

00:25:41.210 --> 00:25:44.300
but you have been
such an inspiration.

00:25:44.300 --> 00:25:47.660
&gt;&gt; Oh, so have you,
Dr. Hayden, thank you.

00:25:47.660 --> 00:25:52.200
&gt;&gt; Now, I remember my favorite
book was called, "Bright April"

00:25:52.200 --> 00:25:57.900
and it was the first time that
I could see myself in a book,

00:25:57.900 --> 00:26:02.150
little girl, she was brown,
she had pigtails, all of that

00:26:02.150 --> 00:26:05.640
and you're talk about not
seeing yourself reflected

00:26:05.640 --> 00:26:08.760
and that's why "Miracle's
Boys" was one of the books

00:26:08.760 --> 00:26:11.170
that people say,
wow I see myself,

00:26:11.170 --> 00:26:13.550
what does that mean
to see yourself?

00:26:13.550 --> 00:26:16.250
&gt;&gt; Well, I think it's so
important looking back

00:26:16.250 --> 00:26:20.420
on the work of Dr. [Inaudible]
who talks about the importance

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:23.620
of young people having
both mirrors and windows.

00:26:23.620 --> 00:26:28.640
So they have books where they
can look in and see a brown girl

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:34.980
or a young Latin boy or an
Asian girl and see some part

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:37.790
of their identity in the
book and that's a mirror

00:26:37.790 --> 00:26:42.110
and it makes them aware of
their presence in a bigger world

00:26:42.110 --> 00:26:46.800
and I think we also talk about
books having windows so you see

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:49.920
into other worlds and for me,
as a young person growing up,

00:26:49.920 --> 00:26:54.190
I had many, many windows into
white worlds and very few books

00:26:54.190 --> 00:26:59.020
where young kids of color
were reflected on the pages

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:00.650
until I think one

00:27:00.650 --> 00:27:06.170
of the earliest books I remember
reading was Virginia Hamilton's

00:27:06.170 --> 00:27:08.500
oh, which Virginia "Zeely"

00:27:08.500 --> 00:27:09.800
&gt;&gt; Oh.

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:12.910
&gt;&gt; And "Zeely" and it was about
two kids and they were going

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:15.480
down south and there was
so much of me on the page

00:27:15.480 --> 00:27:19.800
and another one was Mildred
Taylor's, "Thunder Hear My Cry"

00:27:19.800 --> 00:27:25.320
and it was so eye opening to see
a reflection of myself in Cassie

00:27:25.320 --> 00:27:28.970
and suddenly realize that
there I was on the page

00:27:28.970 --> 00:27:31.570
and that I could be on the
page and not only could I be

00:27:31.570 --> 00:27:37.010
on the page, but I could grow up
to be a woman of color who wrote

00:27:37.010 --> 00:27:39.070
because here was,
Mildred Taylor,

00:27:39.070 --> 00:27:41.130
here was Virginia
Hamilton who were women

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.310
of color telling stories.

00:27:43.310 --> 00:27:46.690
So I think it legitimizes
us in this way

00:27:46.690 --> 00:27:50.810
that we don't realize
our absence until we see

00:27:50.810 --> 00:27:52.880
that presence on the page.

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:54.630
&gt;&gt; Now, you mentioned
wanting to write

00:27:54.630 --> 00:27:58.090
and seeing you could write, how
young were you when you said,

00:27:58.090 --> 00:27:59.580
boy, I like this writing?

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:00.930
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:28:00.930 --> 00:28:03.700
&gt;&gt; Reading, but writing
and I want to produce.

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:06.970
&gt;&gt; I's known I wanted to write
since I was seven and I remember

00:28:06.970 --> 00:28:10.080
as you young person loving
the physical act of writing,

00:28:10.080 --> 00:28:12.190
of holding a pencil and seeing

00:28:12.190 --> 00:28:14.240
that putting letters
together made words

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:17.330
and words made sentences and
sentences made paragraphs

00:28:17.330 --> 00:28:19.830
and that writing was just
that organic, you know,

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:22.330
that all you needed was
that pencil and that paper

00:28:22.330 --> 00:28:26.480
and an imagination and
the rest was there,

00:28:26.480 --> 00:28:29.180
you didn't need any
expensive paraphernalia

00:28:29.180 --> 00:28:31.300
to be able to create art.

00:28:31.300 --> 00:28:35.600
&gt;&gt; Wow. Turning to
the students here,

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:37.920
in terms of paraphernalia
[laughter] and things like that

00:28:37.920 --> 00:28:41.990
because there are so many
distractions and things

00:28:41.990 --> 00:28:46.800
and so people have said, you
know, reading is disappearing

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:50.030
and what's going on with
young people what do you

00:28:50.030 --> 00:28:56.590
&gt;&gt; I don't think I think we
see fewer books sometimes,

00:28:56.590 --> 00:29:00.290
but I don't think
people are not reading,

00:29:00.290 --> 00:29:02.940
I think sometimes we
have to wrestle them

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:08.140
and get their paraphernalia
[laughter] out of their hand

00:29:08.140 --> 00:29:12.730
and remind them of the glory
of reading, but I think,

00:29:12.730 --> 00:29:16.420
as Gene said, young people
love story and they love

00:29:16.420 --> 00:29:23.010
to be engaged that way and there
are many ways in which we read;

00:29:23.010 --> 00:29:25.840
so I think even though we're not
always seeing them with a book

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:28.040
in their hand, sometimes they
have a book in their ear,

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:30.740
sometimes they're
reading on a tablet,

00:29:30.740 --> 00:29:32.820
sometimes someone is
telling them a story,

00:29:32.820 --> 00:29:35.770
sometimes they're creating a
story in their head in some way.

00:29:35.770 --> 00:29:39.780
So I think it's definitely
gotten more challenging,

00:29:39.780 --> 00:29:43.930
but we're a country that
has always had this shift

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:49.950
and so we figure out ways of
engaging people where they are

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:53.300
and if they are in a world where
there's a lot of technology,

00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:57.160
then what are we going to do
to shift them toward reading?

00:29:57.160 --> 00:30:00.550
How do we engage with that
technology to get them

00:30:00.550 --> 00:30:03.730
where they're engaging
with narratives?

00:30:03.730 --> 00:30:08.620
&gt;&gt; Poetry has another
way, a gateway into that.

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:13.200
Now, when did you start with
poetry as another extension of

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:15.890
&gt;&gt; You know, I didn't I
was very afraid of poetry

00:30:15.890 --> 00:30:20.000
when I was a kid, I always
thought it was this, kind of,

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:25.100
secret code that I was emit
to understand and it wasn't

00:30:25.100 --> 00:30:28.390
until I remember
hearing an album,

00:30:28.390 --> 00:30:31.600
my mom was playing this album
and it was Nikki Giovanni

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:35.800
and so it was early spoken word
and I was like, what is that?

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:37.510
And I think it was my
sister that said, "you know,

00:30:37.510 --> 00:30:40.060
that's Nikki Giovanni, that's
poetry" and I'm like, "no,

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:42.190
that's not, like,
I understand that,

00:30:42.190 --> 00:30:43.490
that's not poetry" [laughter]

00:30:43.490 --> 00:30:44.790
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:30:44.790 --> 00:30:48.860
&gt;&gt; And then later on,
writers like Langston Hughes

00:30:48.860 --> 00:30:51.650
and Claude McKay and
all of these poets

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:54.980
who suddenly were speaking
a language I understood,

00:30:54.980 --> 00:30:57.000
unlocked it so that
I could begin

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:02.750
to understand other
poets the more, kind of,

00:31:02.750 --> 00:31:06.570
incomprehensible poets
[laughter] by poetry, you know,

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:09.250
I learned to do the work
of deconstructing poetry

00:31:09.250 --> 00:31:11.100
because I had the
gateway into people like,

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:18.710
Langston Hughes and, you know,
and Nikki Giovanni, Audre Lorde,

00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:22.720
Gwendolyn Brooks, Angelina
Weld Grimké and so many

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:25.300
of the writers who
helped me figure that out.

00:31:25.300 --> 00:31:29.400
&gt;&gt; I remember my grandmothers,
Paul Laurence Dunbar

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:32.290
and I was like, how
could you do the dialect?

00:31:32.290 --> 00:31:33.930
And she said, "I know it"

00:31:33.930 --> 00:31:35.230
&gt;&gt; I know it.

00:31:35.230 --> 00:31:36.530
&gt;&gt; I could do it, I
know what this is.

00:31:36.530 --> 00:31:37.830
&gt;&gt; Had a real big
party in the house

00:31:37.830 --> 00:31:39.130
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:31:39.130 --> 00:31:40.430
&gt;&gt; the other night.

00:31:40.430 --> 00:31:41.730
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:31:41.730 --> 00:31:43.030
&gt;&gt; I love him.

00:31:43.030 --> 00:31:45.230
&gt;&gt; Right. Now, Tupac, we mention
and rap is another way or

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:49.590
&gt;&gt; Yeah. He was an amazing poet,
I mean, Tupac when you look

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:51.660
at The Rose That
Grew From Concrete

00:31:51.660 --> 00:31:56.450
and just the he was not only
a poet, he was an activist

00:31:56.450 --> 00:32:01.200
and I think that's what was so
phenomenal about him and so many

00:32:01.200 --> 00:32:04.350
of the young people
who were rapping,

00:32:04.350 --> 00:32:07.450
they were telling stories,
they were telling history,

00:32:07.450 --> 00:32:09.870
they were breaking down
where we are in the moment

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:12.740
and they were doing it in a
way, going back to shifting,

00:32:12.740 --> 00:32:15.780
where young minds could
understand what they were trying

00:32:15.780 --> 00:32:17.970
to say and they were
asking big questions

00:32:17.970 --> 00:32:20.530
and I think that's what
all good literature does,

00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:23.820
is ask questions of the
reader, of the listener

00:32:23.820 --> 00:32:25.990
about the moment they're in.

00:32:25.990 --> 00:32:31.480
&gt;&gt; Speaking of the moment, your
platform, "reading equals hope

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:37.690
and change" for your time,
how do you see that evolving?

00:32:37.690 --> 00:32:42.210
Because this is an interesting
time to be an ambassador,

00:32:42.210 --> 00:32:44.070
to work with the young people,

00:32:44.070 --> 00:32:48.170
to ask questions,
to answer questions.

00:32:48.170 --> 00:32:54.030
&gt;&gt; So "reading equals hope
times change" is the platform

00:32:54.030 --> 00:32:57.500
that I came up with, that
we came up with that speaks

00:32:57.500 --> 00:33:00.860
to the fact that reading
does allow we go into a book

00:33:00.860 --> 00:33:02.790
because we're hopeful for
something, we're hopeful

00:33:02.790 --> 00:33:05.230
for a good story, we're
hopeful to meet some mirrors

00:33:05.230 --> 00:33:09.210
on the page, we're hopeful
for great characterization

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:13.540
and when we come out of
a book, we're different

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:17.870
and that difference is because
we've met the writer half way,

00:33:17.870 --> 00:33:20.780
and I'm going to talk more
about this in my very short talk

00:33:20.780 --> 00:33:24.290
after this, but I think
that books can change us,

00:33:24.290 --> 00:33:28.030
they can help us begin to
have the bigger conversations,

00:33:28.030 --> 00:33:35.060
they can help us see worlds
and identities and ideas

00:33:35.060 --> 00:33:37.030
that we've never
thought about before

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:39.760
until they've been brought to
the page and we've met them

00:33:39.760 --> 00:33:43.120
on the page; and so I think we
come out of a book different

00:33:43.120 --> 00:33:45.620
than we were than
when we went in it.

00:33:45.620 --> 00:33:47.860
&gt;&gt; Now, one of the
questions I had here

00:33:47.860 --> 00:33:51.130
that you've been
applauded and criticized

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:54.360
for tackling tough
issues, getting back

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:58.640
to respecting young people,
that they can handle discussions

00:33:58.640 --> 00:34:01.840
about tough issues, they're
looking to books sometimes

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:05.110
to help them through it where
they don't have foster care

00:34:05.110 --> 00:34:09.930
and incarceration and why is
that important that we have it?

00:34:09.930 --> 00:34:12.970
&gt;&gt; I think the first thing is
I'm not trying the hear the

00:34:12.970 --> 00:34:15.950
haters so, you know,
they from the beginning

00:34:15.950 --> 00:34:18.060
of time people who have had

00:34:18.060 --> 00:34:19.450
&gt;&gt; Listen to this.

00:34:19.450 --> 00:34:24.160
&gt;&gt; who've tried to create change
have been blasted against,

00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:25.460
right?

00:34:25.460 --> 00:34:27.140
And I think it's because
people are afraid.

00:34:27.140 --> 00:34:29.890
When we look at the issue
of mass incarceration

00:34:29.890 --> 00:34:34.970
in our country I think it's a
sin not to speak to it and not

00:34:34.970 --> 00:34:39.050
to let the young people
who have people who have

00:34:39.050 --> 00:34:41.480
in their families,
in their lives

00:34:41.480 --> 00:34:45.440
who are incarcerated let them
know that they're not alone

00:34:45.440 --> 00:34:49.470
on that journey and that
there is nothing wrong

00:34:49.470 --> 00:34:52.550
with their family makeup and
there is nothing, you know,

00:34:52.550 --> 00:34:56.880
when I wrote, "Visiting Day"
it was because I had grown

00:34:56.880 --> 00:34:59.970
up with my uncle in prison
and it was this, kind of,

00:34:59.970 --> 00:35:03.220
thing we weren't suppose to talk
about and I never understood

00:35:03.220 --> 00:35:06.540
where the shame came from
and looking at it now, again,

00:35:06.540 --> 00:35:09.740
going back to mass
incarceration, how can we try

00:35:09.740 --> 00:35:13.910
to hide something that's
so visible in our society?

00:35:13.910 --> 00:35:17.620
And if we don't talk about it
we can't begin to change it,

00:35:17.620 --> 00:35:20.350
we can just, kind of make
believe it doesn't exist

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:23.940
and so I think any
writer who's going to try

00:35:23.940 --> 00:35:27.570
to have harder conversations,
is going to get criticized.

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:34.170
I remember writing, "If You
Come Softly" where, you know,

00:35:34.170 --> 00:35:38.320
an African American boy gets
killed by cops in a case

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:42.780
of mistaken identity, I remember
people saying this would never

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:45.100
happen, you know?

00:35:45.100 --> 00:35:48.750
Is and this was twenty years ago
and at some point you're kind

00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:51.680
of questioning your own
reality because you think, oh,

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:56.650
maybe this doesn't happen, but
you know it does and that kind

00:35:56.650 --> 00:36:00.260
of gas lighting can happen
when you don't have the proof

00:36:00.260 --> 00:36:04.480
of books and experiences in
the world so that you can go

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:06.900
to that book and say, yeah, you
know, I'm not alone in this,

00:36:06.900 --> 00:36:08.650
yeah, I was right in
thinking about that

00:36:08.650 --> 00:36:10.730
because someone else
is thinking this too.

00:36:10.730 --> 00:36:13.950
&gt;&gt; And young people can
see it and discuss it,

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:16.510
and they can handle it.

00:36:16.510 --> 00:36:18.080
I think they can too.

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:23.370
Now, you also said, "brilliance
is passion recognized"

00:36:23.370 --> 00:36:26.050
which is a wonderful
phrase and in terms

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:28.650
of encouraging young
readers and young authors

00:36:28.650 --> 00:36:32.070
and young poets that
they see that.

00:36:32.070 --> 00:36:33.370
&gt;&gt; Yes that they know.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.070
I think it's so important,
I mean, I was talking

00:36:35.070 --> 00:36:40.060
to my Brooklyn friends and we
were talking about their talents

00:36:40.060 --> 00:36:46.080
and their plans for going to
Duke Ellington and what they do

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:47.400
and it is, I think,

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:50.210
that sometimes people
think there's just one way

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:54.940
to be brilliant, there's maybe
only academic brilliance or

00:36:54.940 --> 00:37:01.560
but I think our brilliance
is our passion recognized

00:37:01.560 --> 00:37:03.310
and celebrated, right?

00:37:03.310 --> 00:37:08.870
When I know that I'm kind of
a good writer and it's nice

00:37:08.870 --> 00:37:14.320
because it's also what I love
to do and I think because I love

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:18.260
to do it, I want to do it
the best that I possibly can

00:37:18.260 --> 00:37:20.590
and I remember having
a teacher say,

00:37:20.590 --> 00:37:22.930
when you chose a career choose
something you love doing

00:37:22.930 --> 00:37:25.540
because you're going to be doing
it for the rest of your life.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:26.840
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:28.360
&gt;&gt; And I think that those
words stayed with me

00:37:28.360 --> 00:37:31.240
because I thought hopefully
I would live a long life

00:37:31.240 --> 00:37:35.820
and the idea of waking up
every day and being unhappy

00:37:35.820 --> 00:37:39.040
with the work you're doing
was heartbreaking to me

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:44.430
and so I honed the thing
that I felt was my brilliance

00:37:44.430 --> 00:37:48.380
and worked at it until it became
the thing I wanted it to be

00:37:48.380 --> 00:37:50.620
in the world, the
stories I wanted to tell,

00:37:50.620 --> 00:37:53.550
and I think everyone much has
that, everyone has that thing

00:37:53.550 --> 00:37:56.960
that they're really good at,
that they really love doing

00:37:56.960 --> 00:38:01.170
and our work as adults,
is to not kill that fire,

00:38:01.170 --> 00:38:06.510
your work as young people, is to
not let that fire get murdered

00:38:06.510 --> 00:38:12.930
and then we get to see all of
that brilliance in the world

00:38:12.930 --> 00:38:16.670
in a way that transforms
it and transforms us.

00:38:16.670 --> 00:38:19.260
&gt;&gt; Can writing help with that?

00:38:19.260 --> 00:38:22.100
As you said, look
through moments in time

00:38:22.100 --> 00:38:25.260
into a more hopeful
place, about writing it,

00:38:25.260 --> 00:38:28.810
expressing it, music,
another way.

00:38:28.810 --> 00:38:30.110
&gt;&gt; I think writing can help

00:38:30.110 --> 00:38:33.850
with everything [laughter]
I think writing is, like,

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:38.370
is the bomb [laughter]
I talk about writing

00:38:38.370 --> 00:38:42.630
because I questions and I
do think that there is a way

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:45.900
where we can sit and begin
to figure out who we are,

00:38:45.900 --> 00:38:49.040
and who we're becoming, and
what the questions that we have

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:51.720
through writing and
through reading.

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:55.970
So I believe deeply,
deeply in writing and I love

00:38:55.970 --> 00:38:59.960
when young people want to be
writers because I know I'm here

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:02.880
because of Nikki Giovanni, I'm
here because of Toni Morrison,

00:39:02.880 --> 00:39:04.460
I'm here because
of Langston Hughes,

00:39:04.460 --> 00:39:06.040
I'm here because
of Gwendolyn Brooks

00:39:06.040 --> 00:39:10.550
and if they had not come
before me, I wouldn't be here

00:39:10.550 --> 00:39:14.850
and I feel like the same thing
the young people are here

00:39:14.850 --> 00:39:18.710
because of us, because of, you
know, Gene and because of John

00:39:18.710 --> 00:39:22.720
and because of Catherine
and me and let

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:24.820
that circle be unbroken,
you know what?

00:39:24.820 --> 00:39:28.460
People keep coming and telling
their stories because now,

00:39:28.460 --> 00:39:31.210
I mean, y' all must have
some amazing stories to tell

00:39:31.210 --> 00:39:33.330
about this moment in time.

00:39:33.330 --> 00:39:35.700
&gt;&gt; Oh, I see you're nodding.

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:38.270
Do we have time for a few

00:39:38.270 --> 00:39:41.790
&gt;&gt; I think you've
got some remarks.

00:39:41.790 --> 00:39:43.090
&gt;&gt; Remarks.

00:39:43.090 --> 00:39:44.630
&gt;&gt; If you want to go ahead
and then we'll respond

00:39:44.630 --> 00:39:46.310
to questions, how about that?

00:39:46.310 --> 00:39:47.610
&gt;&gt; Okay.

00:39:47.610 --> 00:39:48.910
&gt;&gt; Is that

00:39:48.910 --> 00:39:50.210
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:39:50.210 --> 00:39:51.510
&gt;&gt; Gene has my speech.

00:39:51.510 --> 00:39:52.810
&gt;&gt; [Laughter]

00:39:52.810 --> 00:39:54.110
&gt;&gt; Thank you, this one.

00:39:54.110 --> 00:39:58.620
&gt;&gt; And I am going to exit.

00:39:58.620 --> 00:39:59.920
&gt;&gt; Thanks, Dr. Hayden.

