00:47:00.050 --> 00:47:02.360
"Your world is as
big as you make it.

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:07.150
I know, for I used to abide in
the narrowest nest in a corner,

00:47:07.150 --> 00:47:09.830
my wings pressing
close to my side.

00:47:09.830 --> 00:47:12.070
But I sighted the
distant horizon

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:16.050
where the skyline encircled
the sea and I throbbed

00:47:16.050 --> 00:47:19.550
with a burning desire to
travel this immensity.

00:47:19.550 --> 00:47:23.250
I battered the cordons around
me and cradled my wings

00:47:23.250 --> 00:47:31.840
on the breeze, then soared
to the uttermost reaches

00:47:31.840 --> 00:47:35.660
with rapture, with
power, with ease!"

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:40.330
I wish I had written that
poem because I didn't.

00:47:40.330 --> 00:47:44.520
It was written by the poet
Georgia Douglas Johnson

00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:48.350
who for more than 40 years
hosted a salon right here

00:47:48.350 --> 00:47:53.290
in D.C. on Smith Street S.W.
for those you who don't know,

00:47:53.290 --> 00:47:58.530
a salon is basically a gathering
where you come and eat food,

00:47:58.530 --> 00:48:03.110
drink about wine
and organic milk,

00:48:05.800 --> 00:48:07.470
young people [laughter] read
your work and read the work

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:11.930
of others, maybe get a
cipher going and share ideas

00:48:11.930 --> 00:48:15.820
about the world and through
the sharing of these ideas,

00:48:15.820 --> 00:48:18.180
you begin to change
your own way of image

00:48:18.180 --> 00:48:24.630
and the way others think,
but it starts with gathering.

00:48:24.630 --> 00:48:29.220
Through Douglas' salon came some
of the most influential writers

00:48:29.220 --> 00:48:34.540
of the Harlem Renaissance from
Alain Locke, to Langston Hughes

00:48:34.540 --> 00:48:38.760
from Angelina Weld Grimké, to
Jean Toomer poets that I hope

00:48:38.760 --> 00:48:40.110
by the end of my ten year

00:48:40.110 --> 00:48:44.050
as National Ambassador I'll
know how to pronounce the word

00:48:44.050 --> 00:48:48.950
and we will all know them.

00:48:48.950 --> 00:48:52.600
Reading equals hope
times change.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:56.680
When Georgia Douglas Johnson
began those writing salons no

00:48:56.680 --> 00:49:00.690
one knew that the Harlem
Renaissance would take a very

00:49:00.690 --> 00:49:03.600
important place in history.

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:06.510
No one knew that one day
Mildred Taylor would write,

00:49:06.510 --> 00:49:10.300
"Roll of Thunder, Hear My Cry"
that Gene Yang would write,

00:49:10.300 --> 00:49:14.010
"American Born Chinese" that
Simon J. Ortiz would write

00:49:14.010 --> 00:49:15.570
"The People Shall Continue"

00:49:15.570 --> 00:49:19.490
or Sherman Alexie would one day
write, "The Absolute True Diary

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:22.670
of a Part time Indian"
these books,

00:49:22.670 --> 00:49:26.920
these writers were decades
away from that moment,

00:49:26.920 --> 00:49:29.580
many were not even born yet.

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:34.050
The people in Douglas'
salon walked into that room

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:37.090
with a books they were writing
and books they were reading,

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:41.350
they walked into that salon with
hope, they read, they talked,

00:49:41.350 --> 00:49:43.600
they laughed, they
drank, their wine

00:49:43.600 --> 00:49:48.000
and milk [laughter] they sang
and they changed the world

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:54.430
because of them I am, because
of them we are gathered here.

00:49:54.430 --> 00:49:57.430
Yesterday my family and I spent
the day at the American Museum

00:49:57.430 --> 00:50:00.470
of African American
History and Culture; again,

00:50:00.470 --> 00:50:04.180
right here in D.C. it took
over one hundred years to make

00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:06.810
that museum a reality.

00:50:06.810 --> 00:50:10.380
First it was dreamed,
then it was built,

00:50:10.380 --> 00:50:13.480
then people open their trunks
and suitcases and books

00:50:13.480 --> 00:50:18.020
and pulled history of African
Americans in this country

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:21.370
from the crevices into which
that history was delicately

00:50:21.370 --> 00:50:23.950
and lovingly packed away.

00:50:23.950 --> 00:50:25.790
They knew a time would come

00:50:25.790 --> 00:50:31.160
when that history need
a home now is the time.

00:50:31.160 --> 00:50:33.420
As National Ambassador,
my hope is

00:50:33.420 --> 00:50:36.600
to begin conversations
our country is hungry,

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:39.190
but off times, afraid to have.

00:50:39.190 --> 00:50:42.910
Some days this place feels
like a country divided,

00:50:42.910 --> 00:50:48.430
a country in despair, a country
hungry for a way out of no way,

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:52.310
but what the books will tell
us and continue to show us is

00:50:52.310 --> 00:50:56.290
that there is magic in this
moment we're living in now.

00:50:56.290 --> 00:50:58.580
There is so much possibility

00:50:58.580 --> 00:51:00.960
and to the young people
gathered here today,

00:51:00.960 --> 00:51:04.960
that power to create
change is in your hearts,

00:51:04.960 --> 00:51:09.320
in your heads, in your hands.

00:51:09.320 --> 00:51:12.040
I am often asked
about my writing,

00:51:12.040 --> 00:51:13.690
when you write this
book or that book,

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:16.120
what were you trying to teach?

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:20.470
And my answer is always the
same I don't write to teach,

00:51:20.470 --> 00:51:24.410
I write to learn, I write
because I have so many questions

00:51:24.410 --> 00:51:27.690
that only I can answer and
the way can I answer them is

00:51:27.690 --> 00:51:29.720
by putting pen to paper,

00:51:29.720 --> 00:51:32.140
the only way I can find
the hope I'm looking

00:51:32.140 --> 00:51:36.130
for in a particular moment, is
to put that hope on the page

00:51:36.130 --> 00:51:39.430
and when I'm done, like many
writers, my hope has been

00:51:39.430 --> 00:51:42.180
that the reader will
meet me halfway.

00:51:42.180 --> 00:51:45.780
Bring their own ideas
and experiences and hope

00:51:45.780 --> 00:51:47.860
to the narrative I've created.

00:51:47.860 --> 00:51:51.230
So my hope for the next two
years is that we come together

00:51:51.230 --> 00:51:55.520
in many rooms to talk, that
we meet the authors halfway

00:51:55.520 --> 00:51:58.440
and talk about what our
hopes are for the future,

00:51:58.440 --> 00:52:03.200
your equations, our plans for
change, that we hold salons

00:52:03.200 --> 00:52:08.420
and classrooms and libraries and
book stores and living rooms,

00:52:08.420 --> 00:52:10.760
around kitchen tables
and playgrounds,

00:52:10.760 --> 00:52:13.490
at hair salons and barbershops.

00:52:13.490 --> 00:52:16.630
That we find the books that
tell the stories we need to hear

00:52:16.630 --> 00:52:19.590
and use those stories to
write the next chapter

00:52:19.590 --> 00:52:22.090
in this country's history.

00:52:22.090 --> 00:52:24.110
That we remember
that there was a time

00:52:24.110 --> 00:52:27.920
when people were not
allowed to learn to read

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:31.800
because reading led to freedom.

00:52:31.800 --> 00:52:38.840
It's a lot of things being
in this room, at this podium,

00:52:38.840 --> 00:52:44.380
in front of the all of you in
this moment in time, it's scary,

00:52:44.380 --> 00:52:46.460
it's thrilling, its
mind blowing,

00:52:46.460 --> 00:52:49.150
it's imagining the unimaginable.

00:52:49.150 --> 00:52:51.740
The writer, the activist
Audrey Lorde said we can sit

00:52:51.740 --> 00:52:53.810
in our corners mute as bottles

00:52:53.810 --> 00:52:56.520
and we will still
be no less afraid.

00:52:56.520 --> 00:53:01.150
I believe that reading equals
hope, hopes times change,

00:53:01.150 --> 00:53:04.960
I believe that me plus
you equals a conversation,

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:08.560
I believe that hope
minus fear equals change,

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:13.110
I that believe listening plus
hearing minus judgment equals

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:17.380
friendship, these are
just a few of my equations

00:53:17.380 --> 00:53:23.510
in the next two years I'm
eager to gather and hear yours.

